name: Pamela Conn Beall
comments: Born in Lincoln, Nebraska and raised in Klamath Falls, Oregon. She graduated from Klamath Union High School in 1964 and went on to attend and graduate from Oregon State University in 1968, where she was a member of Alpha Chi Sorority. After college she taught elementary music in the Beaverton school district. There  she met Susan Nipp, Together they created a handwritten songbook they named Wee Sing. Over the past 40+years, Pam and Susan grew and expanded Wee Sing to sell over 65 million copies worldwide, and it became a familiar name in many households.

name: Susan Hagen Nipp
comments: Born and raised in Spokane, Washington, with two brothers. Music surrounded the family as they sang in the church choir, joined in trios and quartets, and played various instruments. She studied piano and flute and was in her high school and college band, orchestra, and choir. She received her Bachelor of Arts degree in music with a minor in education from Whitworth College in Spokane, Washington. Upon graduation, she taught high school English in Washington and later, elementary school music in Oregon, where she also met Pamela Conn Beall. Their mutual love of music and children led them to create a handwritten songbook they named Wee Sing. Over the past 40+years, Pam and Susan grew and expanded Wee Sing to sell over 65 million copies worldwide, and it became a familiar name in many households.

Bob DeCormier recommended Millard Williams for the Columbia trio to Tom Wilson. Otherwise, these is no connection between these two groups.

name: Pizzicato Five
comments: Originally a five-piece unit, they debuted commercially in 1985 under the aegis of Haruomi Hosono . In the early years of their career, Pizzicato Five went through diverse line-up changes, only to find temporary stability (and commercial success) in the early 1990's, when singer/model Maki Nomiya joined Konishi and Takanami. In the mid-1990's, when Pizzicato Five started to gain international recognition, Takanami quit the band, thus leaving Konishi and Nomiya as the only remaining members. The duo officially broke up on March 1, 2001. Known for their prolificacy  and eclecticism, their unique retro-futuristic sound and fashion sense made them (at least for Western audiences) the epitome of the so-called Shibuya-kei (Shibuya Style).

name: Igor Gorin
comments: Born in the small village of Grodek (today Horodok, Lviv Oblast) in the Austro-Hungarian Empire. In 1919, when he was 15, he moved with his family to Vienna, Austria. There he studied at the Vienna Music Academy from 1926 to 1929, studying piano, music theory and formal voice training. He subsequently joined a Czech opera touring company and finally the Vienna Volksoper in 1930. His roles included Tonio, Germont, Figaro, Rigoletto, Renato, Wolfram, Escamillo and Valentin. In 1933, at the rise of the Nazi empire, he emigrated to the US. In 1939, he married Mary Smith in May and became a naturalized U.S. citizen in July. From this point forward, his career as an opera singer was pretty well determined.

name: Adolph Baller
comments: Born in Brody, Galicia and Lodomeria, Cisleithania, Austria-Hungary (now Ukraine). At age 8, he went to Vienna to study piano with a former student of Franz Liszt. When he was 13 he gave his first solo performance, with the Vienna Philharmonic, following it with performances in all major European capitals. Being Jewish, he escaped from the Nazis and went to Budapest, where he married Edith Strauss-Neustadt, before coming to the United States in 1938. In New York City, he met violinist Yehudi Menuhin and cellist Gabor Rejto. For several years he accompanied Menuhin in performances throughout the world and performed in chamber concerts, being particularly active during World War II with performances for troops deployed overseas. With Gabor Rejto and Roman Totenberg he formed the Alma Trio in 1942-1943 at Menuhin's Alma estate in Los Gatos, California. He also served as a faculty member at Stanford University for over 30 years. Among his most notable students were pianists Jerome Rose, William Corbett Jones, Xenia Boodberg Lee and minimalist pioneer Terry Riley. Another pupil was Nohema Fernández.
